# Project Rules

## Capturing Feedback

Persisting what we learn is valuable. For this project, that persistence lives in the project files, not the auto-memory system.

- **Actively capture durable "gems."** When Jeff corrects you, confirms an approach, states a preference, or surfaces a decision that will matter beyond this conversation, write it down — don't let it evaporate. There's no auto-memory prompting you to do this, so it's on you to notice and record.
- Write anything worth keeping to the right project file, never to memory files (including `MEMORY.md`). How-to-work guidance (corrections, confirmed approaches, engineering rules) goes in this file, in the most relevant section.
- **Keep `.clinerules` stylistic/workflow only — never app logic.** How the rebalancer behaves, why a threshold works the way it does, and similar domain nuance belong in the docs next to the code they describe (e.g. `docs/rebalancer.md`), not here.

## Simplicity Over Compatibility

This app has no external consumers — keep it simple:

- **No backward-compatibility wrappers.** When refactoring, remove the old interface entirely and update all call sites. Don't leave thin wrappers "just in case."
- **Before making backward-incompatible changes**, warn the user: describe what's changing, which call sites will break, and what the risks are (e.g. runtime errors if something was missed). Then proceed only after acknowledgment.

## Code Style

- Prefer one function that handles multiple cases via parameters over duplicated functions with near-identical logic.
- **Treat the root cause, not the symptom.** Before writing a fix, identify the underlying logic failure and address it directly. Don't add guards or workarounds that produce the correct output while leaving the underlying flaw in place. Ask "what general invariant is being violated?" and fix that — if your first idea only handles the exact case observed (e.g. "skip accounts with one position"), keep thinking until you find the condition covering all variants. The user shouldn't have to guide you to the deeper fix through a series of "what about X?" questions.

## Git

- **Never commit without explicit user approval.** When changes are ready to commit, present a summary of what will be committed and ask for confirmation before running `git commit`.
- **Always commit directly to `main` — never create feature branches.** This is a solo project with trunk-based development; commit to mainline every time.
